    <title>Approval voting</title>
    <id>1857</id>
    <revision>
      <id>430422258</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-22T22:48:54Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>Chzz</username>
        <id>6996885</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>/* Uses */de-link [[England]] ([[WP:OVERLINK]]); clean up, replaced: [[England]] → England using [[Project:AWB|AWB]]</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">[[Image:Approval ballot.svg|thumb|right|On an approval ballot, the voter can vote for any number of candidates]]

{{Electoral systems}}

'''Approval voting''' is a [[Voting system#Single-winner methods|single-winner voting system]] used for [[election]]s. Each voter may vote for (or 'approve' of) as many of the candidates as the voter wishes.  The winner is the candidate receiving the most votes.  Each voter may vote for any combination of candidates and may give each candidate at most one vote.&lt;ref&gt;Brams, Steven and Fishburn, Peter (1983). ''Approval Voting'', Boston: Birkhäuser, p. 3&lt;/ref&gt;

The system was described in 1976 by Guy Ottewell&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.universalworkshop.com/ARVOfull.htm |title=Arithmetic of Voting (full text) |publisher=Universal Workshop |date= |accessdate=2010-05-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; and also by [[Robert J. Weber]], who coined the term &quot;approval voting.&quot; It was more fully published in 1978 by political scientist [[Steven Brams]] and mathematician [[Peter Fishburn]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal | doi = 10.2307/1955105 | author = Brams, Steven and Fishburn, Peter | year = 1978 | title = Approval Voting | jstor =  1955105| journal = American Political Science Review | volume = 72 | issue = 3 | pages = 831–847 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Theory ==

Approval voting can be considered a form of [[range voting]], with the range restricted to two values, 0 and 1. Approval voting can also be compared to [[plurality voting system|plurality voting]], without the rule that discards ballots which vote for more than one candidate.

Ballots which mark every candidate the same (whether yes or no) have no effect on the outcome of the election. Each ballot can therefore be viewed as a small &quot;delta&quot; which separates two groups of candidates, or a single-pair of ranks (e.g. if a ballot indicates that A &amp; C are approved and B &amp; D are not, the ballot can be considered to convey the ranking [A=C]&gt;[B=D]).

== Uses ==

Approval voting has been adopted by the [[Mathematical Association of America]] (1986),&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.maa.org/aboutmaa/bylaws03.html |title=MAA Bylaws |publisher=Maa.org |date=2007-08-05 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; the Institute of Management Sciences (1987) (now the [[Institute for Operations Research and the Management Sciences]]),&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.informs.org/downloadfile.php?i=a1d0c6e83f027327d8461063f4ac58a6 INFORMS bylaws], p. 7&lt;/ref&gt; the [[American Statistical Association]] (1987),&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.amstat.org/about/polproc/index.cfm?fuseaction=bylaws ASA Bylaws]{{dead link|date=May 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]] (1987).  According to Steven J. Brams and Peter C. Fishburn, the IEEE board in 2002 rescinded its decision to use approval voting. IEEE Executive Director Daniel J. Senese stated that approval voting was abandoned because &quot;few of our members were using it and it was felt that it was no longer needed.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/gsas/dept/politics/faculty/brams/theory_to_practice.pdf |title=Going from Theory to Practice: The Mixed Success of Approval Voting |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-05-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; Approval voting also was used for Dartmouth Alumni Association elections for seats on the College Board of Trustees, but after some controversy&lt;ref&gt;[http://thedartmouth.com/2009/04/03/opinion/verbum VERBUM ULTIMUM Making Amends], April 2, 2009, ''Editorial, The Dartmouth''&lt;/ref&gt; it was replaced with traditional runoff elections by an alumni vote of 82% to 18% in 2009.&lt;ref&gt;[http://alumni.dartmouth.edu/news.aspx?id=493 Dartmouth Alumni Association Election Results: New Executive Committee Elected; Constitutional Amendment Passes], May 9, 2009, ''Dartmouth Office of Alumni Relations''&lt;/ref&gt; Dartmouth students used approval voting to elect their student body president in 2011; the winner secured the support of 41% of voters against several write-in candidates.&lt;ref&gt;[http://thelittlegreenblog.blogspot.com/2011/04/hix-12-dartmouth-student-body-both.html Hix '12, Dartmouth Student Body, both shafted in student election], April 16, 2011, ''The Little Green Blog''&lt;/ref&gt;

&lt;span id=&quot;Historical_use&quot;&gt;Historically, several voting methods which incorporate aspects of approval voting have been used:&lt;/span&gt;
* Approving voting was used for [[papal conclave]]s between 1294 and 1621, with an average of about forty cardinals engaging in repeated rounds of voting until one candidate was listed on at least two-thirds of ballots.&lt;ref name=&quot;colomer&quot;&gt;{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1162/002219598551616 | author = Josep M. Colomer and Iain McLean. | year = 1998 | title = Electing Popes: Approval Balloting and Qualified-Majority Rule | url = | journal = The Journal of Interdisciplinary History | volume = 29 | issue = 1| pages = 1–22 }}&lt;/ref&gt;
* In the 13th through 18th centuries, the [[Republic of Venice]] elected the [[Doge of Venice]] using a multi-stage process that featured random selection and voting which allowed approval of multiple candidates and required a supermajority.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1007/BF00135090 | author = Lines, Marji | year = 1986 | title = Approval Voting and Strategy Analysis: A Venetian Example | url =  | journal = Theory and Decision | volume = 20 | issue = 2 | pages = 155–172 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Miranda Mowbray, Dieter Gollmann (2007), {{PDFlink|[http://www.hpl.hp.com/techreports/2007/HPL-2007-28R1.pdf Electing the Doge of Venice: analysis of a 13th Century protocol]}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* According to Steven J. Brams, approval voting was used in 19th century England.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/gsas/dept/politics/faculty/brams/normative_turn.pdf |title=The Normative Turn in Public Choice, p. 4 |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-05-08}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* The selection of the [[United Nations Secretary-General|Secretary-General]] of the [[United Nations]] has involved rounds of approval polling to help discover and build a consensus before a formal vote is held in the Security Council.&lt;ref&gt;{{PDFlink|[http://www.unsgselection.org/files/WisnumurtiGuidelinesSelectingCandidateSecretary-General.pdf The &quot;Wisnumurti Guidelines&quot; for Selecting a Candidate for Secretary-General]}}
&lt;/ref&gt;

== Effect on elections ==

Approval voting advocates [[Steven Brams]] and [[Dudley R. Herschbach]] predict that approval voting should increase voter participation, prevent minor-party candidates from being spoilers, and reduce negative campaigning.&lt;ref&gt;Brams and Herschbach {{cite journal|title=The Science of Elections|doi=10.1126/science.292.5521.1449|journal=Science|volume=292|issue=5521|page=1449|year=2001|author=Brams, S. J.|pmid=11379606|last2=Herschbach|first2=DR}}&lt;/ref&gt; The effect of this system as an [[electoral reform]] measure is not without critics, however. [[FairVote]] has a position paper&lt;ref&gt;[http://archive.fairvote.org/index.php?page=1920 Why IRV]&lt;/ref&gt; arguing that approval voting has three flaws that undercut it as a method of voting and political vehicle. They argue that it can result in the defeat of a candidate who would win an absolute majority in a plurality system, can allow a candidate to win who might not win any support in a plurality elections, and has incentives for [[tactical voting]].

One study